  "articleSummary": "This article critiques the dogmatic application of the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP), arguing that developers who prioritize arbitrary code size limits over conceptual cohesion produce fragmented, unmaintainable architectures. Drawing on examples from React/Redux and Unix philosophy, the author demonstrates how over-fragmentation creates \"file system shrapnel,\" brittle tests, and excessive cognitive load that severely hampers development velocity. Written as a critical yet pragmatic analysis with a satirical/rant-like edge, the piece relies heavily on architectural and structural metaphors (e.g., \"dismembered architecture,\" \"Rube Goldberg patterns,\" \"archaeological digs\") to frame the issue. It targets software engineers, architects, and engineering managers seeking to replace rigid modularity rules with cohesive, pragmatic design practices.",
